One of the four planned demolished buildings during the Paris Commune. The current one was rebuilt later. The building is beautiful.

A very special and interesting museum-library. Specialized in the general, political, military, social and administrative history of France, from the Revolution to the First World War. Originally it was the private mansion of Adolphe Thiers, president of the French Republic from 1871 to 1873. In 1905, Adolphe Thiers' sister-in-law, Félicie Dosne, donated it to the Institut de France “so that it can be allocated to the creation of a modern library and more particularly of French history”. To underline the kindness of the library managers and staff.
The website ignores the war crimes of Thiers, responsible for the massacre of more than 20,000 Parisian Communards in 1871. Shame on the Institute and its selective memory.

Magnificent private mansion at the end of the 19th century, symbol of the extreme political tensions of the beginnings of the 3rd Republic. The Communards had destroyed the Thiers mansion: it was rebuilt even more grandiosely with public funds, according to a special law. Today, it is the headquarters of a foundation dedicated to historical research on the period 1789-1914. A place steeped in history, which can be visited by appointment.
